":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes L'Engenour had at least 3 sons with Richard Eton de Pulford."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1297–Male":"1297–Surnud","1303–Male":"1303–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","abt 1303":"umbes 1303","1303":"1303","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","abt 1297":"umbes 1297","abt. 1295":"umbes 1295","Eton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1297–Male":"1297–Kuollut","1303–Male":"1303–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","abt 1303":"noin 1303","1303":"1303","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","abt 1297":"noin 1297","abt. 1295":"noin 1295","Eton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1295–Male":"1295–Décédé","1297–Male":"1297–Décédé","1303–Male":"1303–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","abt 1303":"environ 1303","1303":"1303","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","abt 1297":"environ 1297","abt. 1295":"environ 1295","Eton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Agnes L'Engenour a eu au moins 3 fils avec Richard Eton de Pulford."},"de":{"–":"Ve